Kafka Connect Integration
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Apache Kafka concepts (topics, producers, consumers)
Familiarity with Linux command line
Basic knowledge of JSON configuration files
Understanding of relational databases (PostgreSQL)
Completed previous Kafka labs or equivalent experience
Learning Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Install and configure Kafka Connect in standalone mode
Create and deploy sink connectors to external systems
Push streaming data from Kafka topics to PostgreSQL database
Push streaming data from Kafka topics to local file system (S3 alternative)
Monitor and verify connector operations
Environment Setup
System Requirements
Linux machine with sudo privileges
Minimum 4GB RAM
10GB free disk space
Install Required Software
1. Install Java (if not already installed)

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y openjdk-11-jdk
java -version
2. Download and Install Kafka

cd ~
wget https://archive.apache.org/dist/kafka/3.5.1/kafka_2.13-3.5.1.tgz
tar -xzf kafka_2.13-3.5.1.tgz
cd kafka_2.13-3.5.1
export KAFKA_HOME=$(pwd)
3. Install PostgreSQL

sudo apt install -y postgresql postgresql-contrib
sudo systemctl start postgresql
sudo systemctl enable postgresql
4. Download JDBC Connector for PostgreSQL

cd $KAFKA_HOME
mkdir -p connectors
cd connectors
wget https://jdbc.postgresql.org/download/postgresql-42.6.0.jar
5. Download Kafka JDBC Connector Plugin

wget https://d1i4a15mxbxib1.cloudfront.net/api/plugins/confluentinc/kafka-connect-jdbc/versions/10.7.4/confluentinc-kafka-connect-jdbc-10.7.4.zip
unzip confluentinc-kafka-connect-jdbc-10.7.4.zip
Task 1: Configure PostgreSQL Database Sink
Step 1: Prepare PostgreSQL Database
Create database and table:

sudo -u postgres psql << EOF
CREATE DATABASE kafkadb;
\c kafkadb
CREATE TABLE user_events (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id VARCHAR(50),
    event_type VARCHAR(50),
    timestamp BIGINT,
    data TEXT
);
\q
EOF
Verify database creation:

sudo -u postgres psql -d kafkadb -c "\dt"
Step 2: Start Kafka Services
Terminal 1 - Start Zookeeper:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/zookeeper-server-start.sh config/zookeeper.properties
Terminal 2 - Start Kafka Broker:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/kafka-server-start.sh config/server.properties
Step 3: Create Kafka Topic
Terminal 3 - Create topic for user events:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/kafka-topics.sh --create \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --partitions 1 \
  --replication-factor 1
Verify topic creation:

bin/kafka-topics.sh --list --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Step 4: Configure JDBC Sink Connector
Create connector configuration file:

cat > config/jdbc-sink-connector.properties << 'EOF'
name=jdbc-sink-connector
connector.class=io.confluent.connect.jdbc.JdbcSinkConnector
tasks.max=1
topics=user-events
connection.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/kafkadb
connection.user=postgres
connection.password=
auto.create=false
auto.evolve=false
insert.mode=insert
pk.mode=none
key.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.storage.StringConverter
value.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.json.JsonConverter
value.converter.schemas.enable=false
EOF
Step 5: Configure Connect Worker
Edit standalone worker configuration:

cat > config/connect-standalone-custom.properties << 'EOF'
bootstrap.servers=localhost:9092
key.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.storage.StringConverter
value.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.json.JsonConverter
key.converter.schemas.enable=false
value.converter.schemas.enable=false
offset.storage.file.filename=/tmp/connect.offsets
offset.flush.interval.ms=10000
plugin.path=/home/ubuntu/kafka_2.13-3.5.1/connectors/confluentinc-kafka-connect-jdbc-10.7.4/lib
EOF
Step 6: Start Kafka Connect
Terminal 4 - Start Connect in standalone mode:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/connect-standalone.sh \
  config/connect-standalone-custom.properties \
  config/jdbc-sink-connector.properties
Wait for connector to start (look for "Connector started" in logs)

Step 7: Produce Test Data
Terminal 5 - Send sample events:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 << EOF
{"user_id":"user001","event_type":"login","timestamp":1699000000,"data":"successful login"}
{"user_id":"user002","event_type":"purchase","timestamp":1699000060,"data":"item: laptop"}
{"user_id":"user003","event_type":"logout","timestamp":1699000120,"data":"session ended"}
EOF
Step 8: Verify Data in PostgreSQL
Check inserted records:

sudo -u postgres psql -d kafkadb -c "SELECT * FROM user_events;"
Expected output:

 id | user_id | event_type |  timestamp  |       data        
----+---------+------------+-------------+-------------------
  1 | user001 | login      | 1699000000  | successful login
  2 | user002 | purchase   | 1699000060  | item: laptop
  3 | user003 | logout     | 1699000120  | session ended
Task 2: Configure File Sink (S3 Alternative)
Step 1: Create File Sink Connector Configuration
Create configuration for local file storage:

cat > config/file-sink-connector.properties << 'EOF'
name=file-sink-connector
connector.class=org.apache.kafka.connect.file.FileStreamSinkConnector
tasks.max=1
topics=user-events
file=/tmp/kafka-output.txt
key.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.storage.StringConverter
value.converter=org.apache.kafka.connect.json.JsonConverter
value.converter.schemas.enable=false
EOF
Step 2: Start File Sink Connector
Stop the previous Connect worker (Ctrl+C in Terminal 4), then restart with both connectors:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/connect-standalone.sh \
  config/connect-standalone-custom.properties \
  config/jdbc-sink-connector.properties \
  config/file-sink-connector.properties
Step 3: Produce Additional Test Data
Terminal 5 - Send more events:

cd $KAFKA_HOME
bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 << EOF
{"user_id":"user004","event_type":"signup","timestamp":1699000180,"data":"new account created"}
{"user_id":"user005","event_type":"view","timestamp":1699000240,"data":"product page viewed"}
EOF
Step 4: Verify File Output
Check the output file:

cat /tmp/kafka-output.txt
Expected content:

{"user_id":"user001","event_type":"login","timestamp":1699000000,"data":"successful login"}
{"user_id":"user002","event_type":"purchase","timestamp":1699000060,"data":"item: laptop"}
{"user_id":"user003","event_type":"logout","timestamp":1699000120,"data":"session ended"}
{"user_id":"user004","event_type":"signup","timestamp":1699000180,"data":"new account created"}
{"user_id":"user005","event_type":"view","timestamp":1699000240,"data":"product page viewed"}
Step 5: Verify Database Updates
Confirm all events are in PostgreSQL:

sudo -u postgres psql -d kafkadb -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM user_events;"
Should show 5 records

Verification
Connector Status Check
View active connectors:

# Check Connect logs for connector status
# Look for lines containing "WorkerSinkTask" and "Committing offsets"
tail -f $KAFKA_HOME/logs/connect.log | grep -i "sink"
End-to-End Data Flow Test
1. Produce a unique test message:

echo '{"user_id":"test999","event_type":"verification","timestamp":1699999999,"data":"end-to-end test"}' | \
bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
2. Verify in PostgreSQL:

sudo -u postgres psql -d kafkadb -c "SELECT * FROM user_events WHERE user_id='test999';"
3. Verify in file:

grep "test999" /tmp/kafka-output.txt
Performance Monitoring
Check consumer lag:

bin/kafka-consumer-groups.sh \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --describe \
  --group connect-file-sink-connector
Troubleshooting Tips
Connector fails to start:

Verify plugin.path in worker configuration points to correct directory
Check PostgreSQL is running: sudo systemctl status postgresql
Ensure JDBC driver is in the plugin path
No data appearing in PostgreSQL:

Verify database credentials in connector config
Check table exists: sudo -u postgres psql -d kafkadb -c "\dt"
Review Connect logs for errors: tail -f logs/connect.log
File sink not writing:

Ensure /tmp directory has write permissions
Check if file exists: ls -l /tmp/kafka-output.txt
Verify connector is running in Connect logs
Connection refused errors:

Confirm Kafka broker is running on port 9092
Check Zookeeper is running on port 2181
Verify bootstrap.servers in configurations
Conclusion
You have successfully:

Configured Kafka Connect in standalone mode
Created a JDBC sink connector to stream data from Kafka to PostgreSQL
Implemented a file sink connector as a local alternative to cloud storage
Verified end-to-end data flow from Kafka topics to multiple sinks
Monitored connector operations and data persistence
Key Takeaways:

Kafka Connect provides declarative integration without custom code
Multiple sink connectors can consume from the same topic simultaneously
Connector configurations are reusable and version-controllable
Standalone mode is suitable for development; distributed mode for production
